                  <cell><m>s\compose r^3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>g\compose \var{id}\compose g^{-1}</m></cell>
                  <cell><mdash/></cell>
                  <cell><mdash/></cell>
                  <cell><mdash/></cell>
                  <cell><ndash/></cell>
                  <cell><ndash/></cell>
                  <cell><ndash/></cell>
                  <cell><ndash/></cell>
                  <cell><ndash/></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
              Remember, once a group element appears in a row,
              you don't need to compute a row for that element,
              because you have already found its conjugacy class.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Verify that the class equation correctly calculates <m>|D_4|</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <example xml:id="example_GroupActions_Conj_18">
      <statement>
        <p>
          We can also create a conjugacy table for using permutation notation.
          Here is the conjugacy table for <m>S_3</m> using permutations.
        </p>
        <tabular>
          <row bottom="minor">
            <cell></cell>
